# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gesture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] The gesture is associated with the Ganga-Jamuni culture of South Asia, especially of the Urdu-speaking communities of Uttar Pradesh, Hyderabadi Muslims, and Muhajir people of Pakistan.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] Since the religious greeting of Muslims i.e.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] "Assalamu Alaikum" was interpreted by some in India to be for Muslims only, and Muslims in India lived in a multi-faith and a multi-lingual society, this alternative form of greeting was coined.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] Its use became so pervasive in the high culture of northern and central India that it was not considered inappropriate to reply to 'salaam' with 'aadaab' and vice versa and it was used frequently in non-Muslim households as well.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] The use of *Aadab* is especially popular in the Indian city of Hyderabad, where religious pluralism has been historically emphasized; the Nizam of the region stated: "Hindus and Muslims are like my two eyes ...
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] How can I favor one eye over the other?" In some localities of India and Pakistan, the phrase and gesture has decreased in use because it is perceived as insufficiently Islamic compared to other greetings, though it is preferred by many who still use it due to its inclusive nature.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] The gesture involves raising the right hand towards the face with palm inwards such that it is in front of the eyes and the finger tips are almost touching the forehead, as the upper torso is bent forward.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] It is typical for the person to say "*adab arz hai*" (Nastaleeq: آداب عرض ہے, Devanagari: आदाब अर्ज़ है), meaning "I offer my respects to you", or simply just "*aadab*".
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] It is often answered with the same or the word "*tasleem*" is said as an answer or sometimes it is answered with a facial gesture of acceptance.
[src:gesture/adab-gesture] In popular culture today, the adab is often associated with the courtly culture of the Muslim Nawabs.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:gesture/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Ayer conducts custom research in an attempt to win the advertising business of Nichols-Shepard Co., a manufacturer of agricultural machinery.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1895 – Harlow Gale of the University of Minnesota mails questionnaires to gather opinions about advertising from the public.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Waldron conducts qualitative research for Mahin’s Advertising Agency.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1910s – 1911 can be considered the year marketing research becomes an industry.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] George Frederick leaves his position as editor of *Printers' Ink* to begin his research company, the Business Bourse with clients such as General Electric and the Texas Co.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Eastman creates the Association of National Advertisers which is now known as the Association of National Advertising Managers.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The group’s first project is a postcard questionnaire to determine magazine readership.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The results introduce the concept of duplication of circulation.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Eastman starts his own company, the Eastman Research Bureau which boasts clients such as *Cosmopolitan, Christian Herald*, and General Electric.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Daniel Starch tests reader recognition levels of magazine and newspaper advertisements and editorial content.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] George Gallup begins measuring advertising readership.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] George Gallup validates his survey methodology by using the same tools polling voters during public elections.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] This allows him to successfully compare and validate his study's results against the election’s results.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1940s – Post World War II, the U.S. sees a large increase in the number of market research companies.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1950s – Market researchers focus on improving methods and measures.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] In their search for a single-number statistic to capture the overall performance of the advertising creative, Day-After-Recall (DAR) is created.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1960s – Qualitative focus groups gain in popularity.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] In addition, some advertisers call for more rigorous measurement of the in-market effectiveness of advertising in order to provide better accountability for the large amounts being spent on advertising.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] In response, Seymour Smith and Associates, using Advertising Research Foundation data as a jumping-off point, develops the Communicus System, a comprehensive approach to isolating the in-market impact of advertising across media.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1970s – Computers emerge as business tools, allowing researchers to conduct large-scale data manipulations.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 175) Multiple studies prove DAR (Recall) scores do not predict sales.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The measure, persuasion, also known as motivation, is validated as a predictor of sales.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The measure known as “breakthrough” is re-examined by researchers who make a distinction between the attention-getting power of the creative execution (attention) and how well “branded” the ad is (brand linkage).
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Herbert Krugman seeks to measure non-verbal measures biologically by tracking brain wave activities as respondents watch commercials.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] (Krugman) Others experiment with galvanic skin response, voice pitch analysis, and eye-tracking.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1980s – Researchers begin to view commercials as a “structured flow of experience” rather than a single unit to be rated on the whole, creating moment-by-moment systems such as the dial-a-meter.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 1990s – Ameritest Research creates Picture Sorts to provide accurate non-verbal measurements in a moment-by-moment system.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Picture Sorts results are graphed to visually represent commercial viewers' moment-by-moment image recognition (Flow of Attention), positive and negative feelings (Flow of Emotion), and brand values (Flow of Meaning).
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Trends in in-market tracking include a greater focus on the multimedia nature of entire advertising campaigns.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] 2000s – Global advertisers seek an integrated marketing research system that will work worldwide so they can compare results across countries.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] For a look at trends predicted for advertising research in the 21st century, see Seven Trends for the Future.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Robert Heath publishes the seminal and controversial monograph “The Hidden Power of Advertising” which challenged the traditional models used in advertising research and shows how most advertising is processed at an emotional level (not a rational level).
[src:gesture/advertising-research] His monograph leads to re-examination of in-market research approaches that compare the behaviors of those who have seen advertising versus those who have not, such as the Communicus System, and the development of brand new pretesting systems such as the OTX AdCEP system.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] There are two types of research, customized and syndicated.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Customized research is conducted for a specific client to address that client’s needs.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Only that client has access to the results of the research.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Syndicated research is a single research study conducted by a research company with its results available, for sale, to multiple companies.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Pre-market research can be conducted to optimize advertisements for any medium: radio, television, print (magazine, newspaper or direct mail), outdoor billboard (highway, bus, or train), or Internet.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Different methods would be applied to gather the necessary data appropriately.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Post-testing is conducted after the advertising, either a single ad or an entire multimedia campaign has been run in-market.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The focus is on what the advertising has done for the brand, for example increasing brand awareness, trial, frequency of purchasing.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Pre-testing, also known as copy testing, is a specialized field of marketing research that determines an ad’s effectiveness based on consumer responses, feedback, and behavior.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Pre-testing is conducted before implementing the advertisement to customers.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] A new area of pre-testing driven by the realization that what works on TV does not necessarily translate in other media.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Greater budgets allocated to digital media in particular have driven the need for campaign pre-testing.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The addition of a media planning tool to this testing approach allows advertisers to test the whole campaign, creative and media, and measures the synergies expected with an integrated campaign.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Post-testing/Tracking studies provide either periodic or continuous in-market research monitoring a brand’s performance, including brand awareness, brand preference, product usage and attitudes.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Some post-testing approaches simply track changes over time, while others use various methods to quantify the specific changes produced by advertising—either the campaign as a whole or by the different media utilized.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Beyond survey-based tracking, causal lift methodologies have gained prominence as advertisers seek evidence of actual behavioral change rather than attitudinal shifts.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Because only experiments, not models, can establish causality, holdout-based lift tests are increasingly regarded as the gold standard against which attribution outputs are calibrated.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Where individual-level randomization is impractical—for example, in linear television, out-of-home, or broad digital campaigns—geo experiments offer a causal alternative by randomly assigning non-overlapping geographic regions to treatment or control conditions and comparing aggregate outcomes.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Larsen et al. introduce GeoLift, an open-source framework that uses synthetic control methods to construct a counterfactual for treated regions from a weighted combination of control regions, improving precision when the number of available geos is small.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Overall, advertisers use post-testing to plan future advertising campaigns, so the approaches that provide the most detailed information on the accomplishments of the campaign are most valued.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] With the longitudinal approach, it is possible to go beyond brand awareness, and to isolate the campaign's impact on specific behavioral and perceptual dimensions, and to isolate campaign impact by media.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Attribution models allocate conversion credit across ad exposures using observed user paths rather than experimental manipulation.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] These include rules-based systems such as last-touch or first-touch, as well as data-driven multi-touch attribution (MTA).
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Incrementality experiments are randomized holdout tests that compare outcomes for exposed and unexposed groups.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] They offer a causal alternative to attribution, but research has found that they frequently produce estimates that diverge substantially from attribution-based figures.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] A subsequent large-scale replication using 663 Facebook experiments confirmed that non-experimental methods continue to overestimate causal effects even when flexible machine-learning estimators are applied.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Google developed geo experiments, in which non-overlapping geographic regions are randomly assigned to treatment or control conditions, as a practical method for obtaining causal estimates of advertising return on investment at scale without individual-level randomization.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Facebook's Conversion Lift product similarly uses randomized test and control groups to isolate incremental conversions attributable to ads.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Meta has recommended using lift results to calibrate attribution models when the two diverge.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] In advertising research, **attention** is the qualitative measure of an advertisement's effectiveness in arousing interest in a viewer.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Qualitative is a measurement that is based on peoples emotions and opinions of the advertisement.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Focus Group based methodologies can be used to collect qualitative responses which inform a measure of attention to an advertisement in a simulated environment.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] One example of this is a "dummy advertising vehicle test," in which a test Television Advertisement is shown with control ads in a controlled environment designed to simulate a commercial break on television.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] The test ad is embedded alongside either directly competitive advertising, or ads from non-competing product categories, depending on the advertiser's preference.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Respondents are asked the question "Which of these ads did you find interesting?" If the test ad is spontaneously mentioned, then that response is counted toward the attention score.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Quantitative techniques such as Eye Tracking are used to measure attention and spontaneous response to marketing messages.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Quantitative measurements are based on data and numbers that are gathered from studies based on how people react to the advertisements .
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Attention data using this methodology can be collected in a variety of simulated environments such as at home or work, as well as across a variety of different screens and devices.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] In addition to measuring attention, this data can be used by advertisers to optimize the design and placement of advertisements.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Advertisers like to make people feel things in order to gain their attention.
[src:gesture/advertising-research] Eye-tracking techniques can be measured by observing the eye movement and pupil dilation when looking at an advertisement.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Affect is important in psychology as well as in communication, mostly when it comes to interpersonal communication and non-verbal communication.
[src:gesture/affect-display] In both psychology and communication, there are a multitude of theories that explain affect and its impact on humans and quality of life.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Affect can be taken to indicate an instinctual reaction to stimulation occurring before the typical cognitive processes considered necessary for the formation of a more complex emotion.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Zajonc asserts that this reaction to stimuli is primary for human beings and is the dominant reaction for lower organisms.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Zajonc suggests affective reactions can occur without extensive perceptual and cognitive encoding, and can be made sooner and with greater confidence than cognitive judgments.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Lazarus on the other hand considers affect to be post-cognitive.
[src:gesture/affect-display] That is, affect is elicited only after a certain amount of cognitive processing of information has been accomplished.
[src:gesture/affect-display] A divergence from a narrow reinforcement model for emotion allows for other perspectives on how affect influences emotional development.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Thus, temperament, cognitive development, socialization patterns, and the idiosyncrasies of one's family or subculture are mutually interactive in non-linear ways.
[src:gesture/affect-display] As an example, the temperament of a highly reactive, low self-soothing infant may "disproportionately" affect the process of emotion regulation in the early months of life.
[src:gesture/affect-display] In relation to perception, a type of non-conscious affect may be separate from the cognitive processing of environmental stimuli.
[src:gesture/affect-display] A monohierarchy of perception, affect and cognition considers the roles of arousal, attentional tendencies, affective primacy, evolutionary constraints, and covert perception within the sensing and processing of preferences and discrimination.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Emotions are complex chains of events triggered by certain stimuli.
[src:gesture/affect-display] There is no way to completely describe an emotion by knowing only some of its components.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Verbal reports of feelings are often inaccurate because people may not know exactly what they feel, or they may feel several different emotions at the same time.
[src:gesture/affect-display] There are also situations that arise in which individuals attempt to hide their feelings, and there are some who believe that public and private events seldom coincide exactly, and that words for feelings are generally more ambiguous than are words for objects or events.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Affective responses, on the other hand, are more basic and may be less problematic in terms of assessment.
[src:gesture/affect-display] (requiring) minimal attention to occur and...
[src:gesture/affect-display] (capable of being) activated without intention or awareness" (1989 p.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Arousal is a basic physiological response to the presentation of stimuli.
[src:gesture/affect-display] When this occurs, a non-conscious affective process takes the form of two control mechanisms; one mobilization, and the other immobilization.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Within the human brain, the amygdala regulates an instinctual reaction initiating this arousal process, either freezing the individual or accelerating mobilization.
[src:gesture/affect-display] The arousal response is illustrated in studies focused on reward systems that control food-seeking behavior.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Researchers focused on learning processes and modulatory processes that are present while encoding and retrieving goal values.
[src:gesture/affect-display] When an organism seeks food, the anticipation of reward based on environmental events becomes another influence on food seeking that is separate from the reward of food itself.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Therefore, earning the reward and anticipating the reward are separate processes and both create an excitatory influence of reward-related cues.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Both processes are dissociated at the level of the amygdala and are functionally integrated within larger neural systems.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Mood, like emotion, is an affective state.
[src:gesture/affect-display] However, an emotion tends to have a clear focus (i.e., a self-evident cause), while mood tends to be more unfocused and diffused.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Mood, according to Batson, Shaw, and Oleson (1992), involves tone and intensity and a structured set of beliefs about general expectations of a future experience of pleasure or pain, or of positive or negative affect in the future.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Unlike instant reactions that produce affect or emotion, and that change with expectations of future pleasure or pain, moods, being diffused and unfocused, and thus harder to cope with, can last for days, weeks, months, or even years.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Moods are hypothetical constructs depicting an individual's emotional state.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Researchers typically infer the existence of moods from a variety of behavioral referents.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Positive affect and negative affect represent independent domains of emotion in the general population, and positive affect is strongly linked to social interaction.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Positive and negative daily events show independent relationships to subjective well-being, and positive affect is strongly linked to social activity.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Recent research suggests that "high functional support is related to higher levels of positive affect".
[src:gesture/affect-display] The exact process through which social support is linked to positive affect remains unclear.
[src:gesture/affect-display] The process could derive from predictable, regularized social interaction, from leisure activities where the focus is on relaxation and positive mood, or from the enjoyment of shared activities.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Research has indicated many differences in affective displays due to gender.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Gender, as opposed to sex, is one's self-perception of being masculine or feminine (i.e., a male can perceive himself to be more feminine or a female can perceive herself to be more masculine).
[src:gesture/affect-display] It can also be argued, however, that hormones (typically determined by sex) greatly affect affective displays and mood.
[src:gesture/affect-display] According to studies done in the late '80s and early '90s, infants within their first year of life are not only able to begin recognizing affect displays but can begin mimicking the displays and also begin developing empathy.
[src:gesture/affect-display] A study in 2011 followed up on these earlier studies by testing fifteen 6-12 month old infants' arousal, via pupil dilation, when looking at both positive and negative displays.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Results showed that when presented with negative affect, an infant's pupil will dilate and stay dilated for a longer period of time when compared to neutral affect.
[src:gesture/affect-display] When presented with positive affect however, the pupil dilation is much larger, but stays dilated for shorter amount of time.
[src:gesture/affect-display] While this study does not prove an infant's ability to empathize with others, it does show that infants do recognize and acknowledge both positive and negative displays of emotion.
[src:gesture/affect-display] In the early 2000s over the period of about seven years, a study was done on about 200 children whose mother had "a history of juvenile-onset unipolar depressive disorder" or simply, depression as children themselves.
[src:gesture/affect-display] In the cases of unipolar depression, a person generally displays more negative affect and less positive affect than a person without depression.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Or, they are more likely to show when they are sad or upset, than when they are excited or happy.
[src:gesture/affect-display] This study that was published in 2010 discovered that the children of mothers that have unipolar depression, had lower levels of positive affect when compared to the control group.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Even as the children grew older, while the negative affect began to stay the same, the children still showed consistently lower positive affect.
[src:gesture/affect-display] This study suggests that "Reduced PA [positive affect] may be one source of developmental vulnerability to familial depression..." meaning that while having family with depression, increases the risk of children developing depression, reduced positive affect increases the risk of this development.
[src:gesture/affect-display] But knowing this aspect of depression, might also be able to help prevent the onset of depression in young children well into their adulthood.
[src:gesture/affect-display] There are some diseases, physical disabilities and mental health disorders that can change the way a person's affect displays are conveyed.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Reduced affect is when a person's emotions cannot be properly conveyed or displayed physically.
[src:gesture/affect-display] There is no actual change in how intensely they truly feel emotions; there is simply a disparity between emotions felt and how intensely they are conveyed.
[src:gesture/affect-display] These disorders can greatly affect a person's quality of life, depending on how intense the disability is.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Flat, blunted, and restricted affects refer to a pattern in which an affected person feels an emotion but does not or cannot display it.
[src:gesture/affect-display] A flat affect is the most severe case in which there is little to no display of emotions.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Restricted and blunted affects are less severe.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Disorders involving these reduced affect displays most commonly include schizophrenia, post traumatic stress disorder, depression, autism and traumatic brain injuries.
[src:gesture/affect-display] One study has shown that people with schizophrenia that experience flat affect can also experience difficulty perceiving the emotions of a healthy individual.
[src:gesture/affect-display] People who have facial deformities or paralysis may also be physically incapable of displaying emotions.
[src:gesture/affect-display] This is beginning to be corrected though, through "Facial Reanimation Surgery" which is proving not only to successfully improve a patient's affect displays, but also bettering their psychological health.
[src:gesture/affect-display] There are multiple types of surgeries that can help fix facial paralysis.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Emotions can be displayed in order to elicit desired behaviors from others.
[src:gesture/affect-display] People have been known to display positive emotions in various settings.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Service workers often engage in emotional labor, a strive to maintain positive emotional expressions despite difficulties in working conditions or rude customers, in order to conform to organizational rules.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Such strategic displays are not always effective, since if they are detected, lower customer satisfaction results.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Perhaps the most notable attempt to feign negative emotion could be seen with Nixon's madman theory.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Nixon's administration attempted to make the leaders of other countries think Nixon was mad, and that his behavior was irrational and volatile.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Fearing an unpredictable American response, leaders of hostile Communist Bloc nations would avoid provoking the United States.
[src:gesture/affect-display] This diplomatic strategy was not ultimately successful.
[src:gesture/affect-display] The effectiveness of the strategic display depends on the ability of the expresser to remain undetected.
[src:gesture/affect-display] It may be a risky strategy since, if detected, the person's original intent could be discovered, undermining the future relationship with the target.
[src:gesture/affect-display] According to the appraisal theory of emotions, the experience of emotions is preceded by an evaluation of an object of significance to that individual.
[src:gesture/affect-display] When individuals are seen to display emotions, it serves as a signal to others of an event important to that individual.
[src:gesture/affect-display] Thus, deliberately altering the emotion display toward an object could be used make the targets of the strategic emotion think and behave in ways that benefit the original expresser.
[src:gesture/affect-display] For example, people attempt to hide their expressions during a poker game in order to avoid giving away information to the other players, i.e., keep a poker face.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] In linguistics, **affect** is an attitude or emotion that a speaker brings to an utterance.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] Lexical choices may frame a speaker's affect, such as *slender* (positive affect) vs.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] *scrawny* (negative affect), *thrifty* (positive) vs.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] *stingy* (negative) and *freedom fighter* (positive) vs.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] In many languages of Europe, augmentative derivations are used to express contempt or other negative attitudes toward the noun being so modified, whereas diminutives may express affection; on the other hand, diminutives are frequently used to belittle or be dismissive.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] For instance, in Spanish, a name ending in diminutive *-ito* (masculine) or *-ita* (feminine) may be a term of endearment, but *señorito* "little mister" for *señor* "mister" may be mocking.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] Polish has a range of augmentative and diminutive forms, which express differences in affect.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] So, from *żaba* "a frog", besides *żabucha* for simply a big frog, there is augmentative *żabsko* to express distaste, *żabisko* if the frog is ugly, *żabula* if it is likeably awkward, etc.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] Affect can also be conveyed by more subtle means.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] Duranti, for example, shows that the use of pronouns in Italian narration indicates that the character referred to is important to the narration but is generally also a mark of a positive speaker attitude toward the character.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] In Japanese and Korean, grammatical affect is conveyed both through honorific, polite, and humble language, which affects both nouns and verbal inflection, and through clause-final particles that express a range of speaker emotions and attitudes toward what is being said.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] ʔaː=tʼo béda=ht̪ow béː=yo-w dá-ːʔ-du-w tʃʰó-w. béda ʔaː qʼlá-w=ʔkʰe.
[src:gesture/affect-linguistics] "(But) I don't want to go away from here.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In definitions commonly used in the social sciences and behavioral sciences, aggression is an action or response by an individual that delivers something unpleasant to another person.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Some definitions include that the individual must intend to harm another person.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In an interdisciplinary perspective, aggression is regarded as "an ensemble of mechanisms formed during the course of evolution in order to assert oneself, relatives, or friends against others, to gain or to defend resources (ultimate causes) by harmful damaging means.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] These mechanisms are often motivated by emotions such as fear, frustration, anger, stress, dominance or pleasure (proximate causes).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Sometimes aggressive behavior serves as a stress relief or a subjective feeling of power." Predatory or defensive behavior between members of different species may not be considered aggression in the same sense.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] There are two subtypes of human aggression: (1) controlled-instrumental subtype (purposeful or goal-oriented); and (2) reactive-impulsive subtype (often elicits uncontrollable actions that are inappropriate or undesirable).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression differs from what is commonly called assertiveness, although the terms are often used interchangeably among laypeople (as in phrases such as "an aggressive salesperson").
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] (1939) proposed that aggression was due to frustration, which was described as an unpleasant emotion resulting from any interference with achieving a rewarding goal.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Berkowitz extended this frustration–aggression hypothesis and proposed that it is not so much the frustration as the unpleasant emotion that evokes aggressive tendencies, and that all aversive events produce negative affect and thereby aggressive tendencies, as well as fear tendencies.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression can have adaptive benefits or negative effects.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggressive behavior is an individual or collective social interaction that is a hostile behavior with the intention of inflicting damage or harm.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Two broad categories of aggression are commonly distinguished.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] One includes affective (emotional) and hostile, reactive, or retaliatory aggression that is a response to provocation, and the other includes instrumental, goal-oriented or predatory, in which aggression is used as a means to achieve a goal.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] An example of hostile aggression would be a person who punches someone that insulted him or her.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] An instrumental form of aggression would be armed robbery.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Research on violence from a range of disciplines lend some support to a distinction between affective and predatory aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, some researchers question the usefulness of a hostile versus instrumental distinction in humans, despite its ubiquity in research, because most real-life cases involve mixed motives and interacting causes.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A number of classifications and dimensions of aggression have been suggested.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Classification may also encompass aggression-related emotions (e.g., anger) and mental states (e.g., impulsivity, hostility).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression may occur in response to non-social as well as social factors, and can have a close relationship with stress coping style.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression may be displayed in order to intimidate.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The operative definition of aggression may be affected by moral or political views.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Examples are the axiomatic moral view called the non-aggression principle and the political rules governing the behavior of one country toward another.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Likewise in competitive sports, or in the workplace, some forms of aggression may be sanctioned and others not (see Workplace aggression).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggressive behaviors are associated with adjustment problems and several psychopathological symptoms such as antisocial personality disorder, borderline personality disorder, and intermittent explosive disorder.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Biological approaches conceptualize aggression as an internal energy released by external stimuli, a product of evolution through natural selection, part of genetics, and a product of hormonal fluctuations.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Psychological approaches conceptualize aggression as a destructive instinct, a response to frustration, an affect excited by a negative stimulus, a result of observed learning of society and diversified reinforcement, and a result of variables that affect personal and situational environments.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The term aggression comes from the Latin word *aggressio*, meaning attack.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The Latin was itself a joining of *ad*- and *gradi*-, which meant "step at".
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The first known use dates back to 1611, in the sense of an unprovoked attack.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A psychological sense of "hostile or destructive behavior" dates back to a 1912 English translation of Sigmund Freud's writing.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Alfred Adler theorized about an "aggressive drive" in 1908.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Child raising experts began to refer to aggression, rather than anger, from the 1930s.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Ethologists study aggression as it relates to the interaction and evolution of animals in natural settings.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In such settings aggression can involve bodily contact such as biting, hitting or pushing, but most conflicts are settled by threat displays and intimidating thrusts that cause no physical harm.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This form of aggression may include the display of body size, antlers, claws or teeth; stereotyped signals including facial expressions; vocalizations such as bird song; the release of chemicals; and changes in coloration.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The term agonistic behavior is sometimes used to refer to these forms of behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Most ethologists believe that aggression confers biological advantages.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression may help an animal secure territory, including resources such as food and water.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression between males often occurs to secure mating opportunities, and results in selection of the healthier/more vigorous animal.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression may also occur for self-protection or to protect offspring.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression between groups of animals may also confer advantage; for example, hostile behavior may force a population of animals into a new territory, where the need to adapt to a new environment may lead to an increase in genetic flexibility.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The most apparent type of interspecific aggression is that observed in the interaction between a predator and its prey.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, according to many researchers, predation is not aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A cat does not hiss or arch its back when pursuing a rat, and the active areas in its hypothalamus resemble those that reflect hunger rather than those that reflect aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, others refer to this behavior as predatory aggression, and point out cases that resemble hostile behavior, such as mouse-killing by rats.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In aggressive mimicry a predator has the appearance of a harmless organism or object attractive to the prey; when the prey approaches, the predator attacks.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] An animal defending against a predator may engage in either "fight or flight" or "tend and befriend" in response to predator attack or threat of attack, depending on its estimate of the predator's strength relative to its own.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Alternative defenses include a range of antipredator adaptations, including alarm signals.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] An example of an alarm signal is Nerol, a chemical which is found in the mandibular glands of *Trigona fulviventris* individuals.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Release of Nerol by T. fulviventris individuals in the nest has been shown to decrease the number of individuals leaving the nest by fifty percent, as well as increasing aggressive behaviors like biting.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Alarm signals like nerol can also act as attraction signals; in T. fulviventris, individuals that have been captured by a predator may release nerol to attract nest mates, who will proceed to attack or bite the predator.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Also, an individual is more likely to become aggressive if other aggressive group members are nearby.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] One particular phenomenon – the formation of coordinated coalitions that raid neighboring territories to kill conspecifics – has only been documented in two species in the animal kingdom: 'common' chimpanzees and humans.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression between conspecifics in a group typically involves access to resources and breeding opportunities.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] One of its most common functions is to establish a dominance hierarchy.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This occurs in many species by aggressive encounters between contending males when they are first together in a common environment.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Usually the more aggressive animals become the more dominant.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In test situations, most of the conspecific aggression ceases about 24 hours after the group of animals is brought together.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression has been defined from this viewpoint as "behavior which is intended to increase the social dominance of the organism relative to the dominance position of other organisms".
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Losing confrontations may be called social defeat, and winning or losing is associated with a range of practical and psychological consequences.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Conflicts between animals occur in many contexts, such as between potential mating partners, between parents and offspring, between siblings and between competitors for resources.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Group-living animals may dispute over the direction of travel or the allocation of time to joint activities.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Various factors limit the escalation of aggression, including communicative displays, conventions, and routines.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In addition, following aggressive incidents, various forms of conflict resolution have been observed in mammalian species, particularly in gregarious primates.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] These can mitigate or repair possible adverse consequences, especially for the recipient of aggression who may become vulnerable to attacks by other members of a group.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Conciliatory acts vary by species and may involve specific gestures or simply more proximity and interaction between the individuals involved.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, conflicts over food are rarely followed by post conflict reunions, even though they are the most frequent type in foraging primates.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Other questions that have been considered in the study of primate aggression, including in humans, is how aggression affects the organization of a group, what costs are incurred by aggression, and why some primates avoid aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] For example, bonobo chimpanzee groups are known for low levels of aggression within a partially matriarchal society.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Captive animals including primates may show abnormal levels of social aggression and self-harm that are related to aspects of the physical or social environment; this depends on the species and individual factors such as gender, age and background (e.g., raised wild or captive).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Within ethology, it has long been recognized that there is a relation between aggression, fear, and curiosity.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In this approach, when the inconsistency between perception and expectancy is small, learning as a result of curiosity reduces inconsistency by updating expectancy to match perception.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] If the inconsistency is larger, fear or aggressive behavior may be employed to alter the perception in order to make it match expectancy, depending on the size of the inconsistency as well as the specific context.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Uninhibited fear results in fleeing, thereby removing the inconsistent stimulus from the perceptual field and resolving the inconsistency.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In some cases, thwarted escape may trigger aggressive behavior in an attempt to remove the thwarting stimulus.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Like many behaviors, aggression can be examined in terms of its ability to help an animal itself survive and reproduce, or alternatively to risk survival and reproduction.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This cost–benefit analysis can be looked at in terms of evolution.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, there are profound differences in the extent of acceptance of a biological or evolutionary basis for human aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression can involve violence that may be adaptive under certain circumstances in terms of natural selection.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This is most obviously the case in terms of attacking prey to obtain food, or in anti-predatory defense.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] It may also be the case in competition between members of the same species or subgroup, if the average reward (e.g., status, access to resources, protection of self or kin) outweighs average costs (e.g., injury, exclusion from the group, death).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] There are some hypotheses of specific adaptions for violence in humans under certain circumstances, including for homicide, but it is often unclear what behaviors may have been selected for and what may have been a byproduct, as in the case of collective violence.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Although aggressive encounters are ubiquitous in the animal kingdom, with often high stakes, most encounters that involve aggression may be resolved through posturing, or displaying and trial of strength.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Game theory is used to understand how such behaviors might spread by natural selection within a population, and potentially become 'Evolutionary Stable Strategies'.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] An initial model of resolution of conflicts is the hawk-dove game.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Others include the Sequential assessment model and the Energetic war of attrition.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] These try to understand not just one-off encounters but protracted stand-offs, and mainly differ in the criteria by which an individual decides to give up rather than risk loss and harm in physical conflict (such as through estimates of resource holding potential).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Gender plays an important role in human aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] There are multiple theories that seek to explain findings that males and females of the same species can have differing aggressive behaviors.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] One review concluded that male aggression tended to produce pain or physical injury, whereas female aggression tended towards psychological or social harm.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In general, sexual dimorphism can be attributed to greater intraspecific competition in one sex, either between rivals for access to mates and/or to be chosen by mates.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This may stem from the other gender being constrained by providing greater parental investment, in terms of factors such as gamete production, gestation, lactation, or upbringing of young.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Although there is much variation in species, generally the more physically aggressive sex is the male, particularly in mammals.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In species where parental care by both sexes is required, there tends to be less of a difference.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] When the female can leave the male to care for the offspring, then females may be the larger and more physically aggressive.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Competitiveness despite parental investment has also been observed in some species.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A related factor is the rate at which males and females are able to mate again after producing offspring, and the basic principles of sexual selection are also influenced by ecological factors affecting the ways or extent to which one sex can compete for the other.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The role of such factors in human evolution is controversial.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The pattern of male and female aggression is argued to be consistent with evolved sexually selected behavioral differences, while alternative or complementary views emphasize conventional social roles stemming from physical evolved differences.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggression in women may have evolved to be, on average, less physically dangerous and more covert or indirect.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, there are critiques of using animal behavior to explain human behavior, especially in the application of evolutionary explanations to contemporary human behavior, including differences between genders.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] According to the 2015 *International Encyclopedia of the Social & Behavioral Sciences*, sex differences in aggression is one of the most robust and oldest findings in psychology.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Past meta-analyses in the encyclopedia found males regardless of age engaged in more physical and verbal aggression while small effect for females engaging in more indirect aggression such as rumor spreading or gossiping.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] It also found males tend to engage in more unprovoked aggression at higher frequency than females.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This analysis also conforms with the *Oxford Handbook of Evolutionary Psychology* which reviewed past analysis which found men to use more verbal and physical aggression with the difference being greater in the physical type.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] There are more recent findings that show that differences in male and female aggression appear at about two years of age, though the differences in aggression are more consistent in middle-aged children and adolescence.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Tremblay, Japel and Pérusse (1999) asserted that physically aggressive behaviors such as kicking, biting and hitting are age-typical expressions of innate and spontaneous reactions to biological drives such as anger, hunger, and affiliation.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Girls' relational aggression, meaning non-physical or indirect, tends to increase after age two while physical aggression decreases.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] There was no significant difference in aggression between males and females before two years of age.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A possible explanation for this could be that girls develop language skills more quickly than boys, and therefore have better ways of verbalizing their wants and needs.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] According to the journal of *Aggressive Behaviour*, an analysis across 9 countries found boys reported more in the use of physical aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] At the same time no consistent sex differences emerged within relational aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] It has been found that girls are more likely than boys to use reactive aggression and then retract, but boys are more likely to increase rather than to retract their aggression after their first reaction.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Studies show girls' aggressive tactics included gossip, ostracism, breaking confidences, and criticism of a victim's clothing, appearance, or personality, whereas boys engage in aggression that involves a direct physical and/or verbal assault.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This could be due to the fact that girls' frontal lobes develop earlier than boys, allowing them to self-restrain.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] One factor that shows insignificant differences between male and female aggression is in sports.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In sports, the rate of aggression in both contact and non-contact sports is relatively equal.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Since the establishment of Title IX, female sports have increased in competitiveness and importance, which could contribute to the evening of aggression and the "need to win" attitude between both genders.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Among sex differences found in adult sports were that females have a higher scale of indirect hostility while men have a higher scale of assault.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Another difference found is that men have up to 20 times higher levels of testosterone than women.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Some studies suggest that romantic involvement in adolescence decreases aggression in males and females, but decreases at a higher rate in females.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Females will seem more desirable to their mate if they fit in with society and females that are aggressive do not usually fit well in society.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Female aggression is not considered the norm in society and going against the norm can sometimes prevent one from getting a mate.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, studies have shown that an increasing number of women are getting arrested on domestic violence charges.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In many states, women now account for a quarter to a third of all domestic violence arrests, up from less than 10 percent a decade ago.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The new statistics reflect a reality documented in research: women are perpetrators as well as victims of family violence.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, another equally possible explanation is a case of improved diagnostics: it has become more acceptable for men to report female domestic violence to the authorities while at the same time actual female domestic violence has not increased at all.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This could be the case in a situation where men had become less ashamed of reporting female violence against them⁠‍—‍such a situation could conceivably lead to an increasing number of women being arrested despite the actual number of violent women remaining the same.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In addition, males in competitive sports are often advised by their coaches not to be in intimate relationships based on the premise that they become more docile and less aggressive during an athletic event.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The circumstances in which males and females experience aggression are also different.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A study showed that social anxiety and stress were positively correlated with aggression in males, meaning that as stress and social anxiety increase, so does aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Furthermore, a male with higher social skills has a lower rate of aggressive behavior than a male with lower social skills.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In females, higher rates of aggression were only correlated with higher rates of stress.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Other than biological factors that contribute to aggression, there are physical factors as well.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Regarding sexual dimorphism, humans fall into an intermediate group with moderate sex differences in body size but relatively large testes.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This is a typical pattern of primates where several males and females live together in a group and the male faces an intermediate number of challenges from other males compared to exclusive polygyny and monogamy but frequent sperm competition.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Evolutionary psychology and sociobiology have also discussed and produced theories for some specific forms of male aggression such as sociobiological theories of rape and theories regarding the Cinderella effect.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Many researchers focus on the brain to explain aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Numerous circuits within both neocortical and subcortical structures play a central role in controlling aggressive behavior, depending on the species, and the exact role of pathways may vary depending on the type of trigger or intention.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In mammals, the hypothalamus and periaqueductal gray of the midbrain are critical areas, as shown in studies on cats, rats, and monkeys.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] These brain areas control the expression of both behavioral and autonomic components of aggression in these species, including vocalization.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Electrical stimulation of the hypothalamus causes aggressive behavior and the hypothalamus has receptors that help determine aggression levels based on their interactions with serotonin and vasopressin.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In rodents, activation of estrogen receptor-expressing neurons in the ventrolateral portion of the ventromedial hypothalamus (VMHvl) was found to be sufficient to initiate aggression in both males and females.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Midbrain areas involved in aggression have direct connections with both the brainstem nuclei controlling these functions, and with structures such as the amygdala and prefrontal cortex.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Stimulation of the amygdala results in augmented aggressive behavior in hamsters, while lesions of an evolutionarily homologous area in the lizard greatly reduce competitive drive and aggression (Bauman et al.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In rhesus monkeys, neonatal lesions in the amygdala or hippocampus results in reduced expression of social dominance, related to the regulation of aggression and fear.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Several experiments in attack-primed Syrian golden hamsters, for example, support the claim of circuitry within the amygdala being involved in control of aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The role of the amygdala is less clear in primates and appears to depend more on situational context, with lesions leading to increases in either social affiliatory or aggressive responses.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Amygdalotomy, which involves removing or destroying parts of the amygdala, has been performed on people to reduce their violent behaviour.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The broad area of the cortex known as the prefrontal cortex (PFC) is crucial for self-control and inhibition of impulses, including inhibition of aggression and emotions.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Reduced activity of the prefrontal cortex, in particular its medial and orbitofrontal portions, has been associated with violent/antisocial aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In addition, reduced response inhibition has been found in violent offenders, compared to non-violent offenders.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The role of the chemicals in the brain, particularly neurotransmitters, in aggression has also been examined.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This varies depending on the pathway, the context and other factors such as gender.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A deficit in serotonin has been theorized to have a primary role in causing impulsivity and aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] At least one epigenetic study supports this supposition.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Nevertheless, low levels of serotonin transmission may explain a vulnerability to impulsiveness, potential aggression, and may have an effect through interactions with other neurochemical systems.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] These include dopamine systems which are generally associated with attention and motivation toward rewards, and operate at various levels.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Norepinephrine, also known as noradrenaline, may influence aggression responses both directly and indirectly through the hormonal system, the sympathetic nervous system or the central nervous system (including the brain).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] It appears to have different effects depending on the type of triggering stimulus, for example social isolation/rank versus shock/chemical agitation which appears not to have a linear relationship with aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Similarly, GABA, although associated with inhibitory functions at many CNS synapses, sometimes shows a positive correlation with aggression, including when potentiated by alcohol.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The hormonal neuropeptides vasopressin and oxytocin play a key role in complex social behaviours in many mammals such as regulating attachment, social recognition, and aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Vasopressin has been implicated in male-typical social behaviors which includes aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Oxytocin may have a particular role in regulating female bonds with offspring and mates, including the use of protective aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Initial studies in humans suggest some similar effects.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In human, aggressive behavior has been associated with abnormalities in three principal regulatory systems in the body serotonin systems, catecholamine systems, and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Early androgenization has an organizational effect on the developing brains of both males and females, making more neural circuits that control sexual behavior as well as intermale and interfemale aggression become more sensitive to testosterone.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] There are noticeable sex differences in aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Testosterone is present to a lesser extent in females, who may be more sensitive to its effects.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Animal studies have also indicated a link between incidents of aggression and the individual level of circulating testosterone.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, results in relation to primates, particularly humans, are less clear cut and are at best only suggestive of a positive association in some contexts.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In humans, there is a seasonal variation in aggression associated with changes in testosterone.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] For example, in some primate species, such as rhesus monkeys and baboons, females are more likely to engage in fights around the time of ovulation as well as right before menstruation.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] If the results were the same in humans as they are in rhesus monkeys and baboons, then the increase in aggressive behaviors during ovulation is explained by the decline in estrogen levels.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This makes normal testosterone levels more effective.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Castrated mice and rats exhibit lower levels of aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Males castrated as neonates exhibit low levels of aggression even when given testosterone throughout their development.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The challenge hypothesis outlines the dynamic relationship between plasma testosterone levels and aggression in mating contexts in many species.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] It proposes that testosterone is linked to aggression when it is beneficial for reproduction, such as in mate guarding and preventing the encroachment of intrasexual rivals.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The challenge hypothesis predicts that seasonal patterns in testosterone levels in a species are a function of mating system (monogamy versus polygyny), paternal care, and male-male aggression in seasonal breeders.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This pattern between testosterone and aggression was first observed in seasonally breeding birds, such as the song sparrow, where testosterone levels rise modestly with the onset of the breeding season to support basic reproductive functions.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The hypothesis has been subsequently expanded and modified to predict relationships between testosterone and aggression in other species.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] For example, chimpanzees, which are continuous breeders, show significantly raised testosterone levels and aggressive male-male interactions when receptive and fertile females are present.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Currently, no research has specified a relationship between the modified challenge hypothesis and human behavior, or the human nature of concealed ovulation, although some suggest it may apply.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Another line of research has focused on the proximate effects of circulating testosterone on the nervous system, as mediated by local metabolism within the brain.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Testosterone can be metabolized to estradiol by the enzyme aromatase, or to dihydrotestosterone (DHT) by 5α-reductase.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aromatase is highly expressed in regions involved in the regulation of aggressive behavior, such as the amygdala and hypothalamus.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In studies using genetic knockout techniques in inbred mice, male mice that lacked a functional aromatase enzyme displayed a marked reduction in aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Long-term treatment with estradiol partially restored aggressive behavior, suggesting that the neural conversion of circulating testosterone to estradiol and its effect on estrogen receptors influences inter-male aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In addition, two different estrogen receptors, ERα and ERβ, have been identified as having the ability to exert different effects on aggression in mice.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, the effect of estradiol appears to vary depending on the strain of mouse, and in some strains it reduces aggression during long days (16 h of light), while during short days (8 h of light) estradiol rapidly increases aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Another hypothesis is that testosterone influences brain areas that control behavioral reactions.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Studies in animal models indicate that aggression is affected by several interconnected cortical and subcortical structures within the so-called social behavior network.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] A study involving lesions and electrical-chemical stimulation in rodents and cats revealed that such a neural network consists of the medial amygdala, medial hypothalamus and periaqueductal grey (PAG), and it positively modulates reactive aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Moreover, a study done in human subjects showed that prefrontal-amygdala connectivity is modulated by endogenous testosterone during social emotional behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In human studies, testosterone-aggression research has also focused on the role of the orbitofrontal cortex (OFC).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This brain area is strongly associated with impulse control and self-regulation systems that integrate emotion, motivation, and cognition to guide context-appropriate behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Patients with localized lesions to the OFC engage in heightened reactive aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Aggressive behavior may be regulated by testosterone via reduced medial OFC engagement following social provocation.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] When measuring participants' salivary testosterone, higher levels can predict subsequent aggressive behavioral reactions to unfairness faced during a task.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Moreover, brain scanning with fMRI shows reduced activity in the medial OFC during such reactions.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Such findings may suggest that a specific brain region, the OFC, is a key factor in understanding reactive aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Scientists have for a long time been interested in the relationship between testosterone and aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In most species, males are more aggressive than females.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Castration of males usually has a pacifying effect on aggressive behavior in males.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In humans, males engage in crime and especially violent crime more than females.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The involvement in crime usually rises in the early teens to mid teens which happen at the same time as testosterone levels rise.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Research on the relationship between testosterone and aggression is difficult since the only reliable measurement of brain testosterone is by a lumbar puncture which is not done for research purposes.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Studies therefore have often instead used more unreliable measurements from blood or saliva.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] No specific response of testosterone levels to competition was observed in female athletes, although a mood difference was noted.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In addition, some experiments have failed to find a relationship between testosterone levels and aggression in humans.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The possible correlation between testosterone and aggression could explain the "roid rage" that can result from anabolic steroid use, although an effect of abnormally high levels of steroids does not prove an effect at physiological levels.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) is the most abundant circulating androgen hormone and can be rapidly metabolized within target tissues into potent androgens and estrogens.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Gonadal steroids generally regulate aggression during the breeding season, but non-gonadal steroids may regulate aggression during the non-breeding season.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Castration of various species in the non-breeding season has no effect on territorial aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In several avian studies, circulating DHEA has been found to be elevated in birds during the non-breeding season.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] These data support the idea that non-breeding birds combine adrenal and/or gonadal DHEA synthesis with neural DHEA metabolism to maintain territorial behavior when gonadal testosterone secretion is low.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Similar results have been found in studies involving different strains of rats, mice, and hamsters.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] DHEA levels also have been studied in humans and may play a role in human aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Circulating DHEAS (its sulfated ester) levels rise during adrenarche (≈7 years of age) while plasma testosterone levels are relatively low.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] This implies that aggression in pre-pubertal children with aggressive conduct disorder might be correlated with plasma DHEAS rather than plasma testosterone, suggesting an important link between DHEAS and human aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Glucocorticoid hormones have an important role in regulating aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In adult rats, acute injections of corticosterone promote aggressive behavior, and acute reduction of corticosterone decreases aggression; however, chronic reduction of corticosterone levels can produce abnormally aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In addition, glucocorticoids affect the development of aggression and the establishment of social hierarchies.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Adult mice with low baseline levels of corticosterone are more likely to become dominant than mice with high baseline corticosterone levels.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Glucocorticoids are released by the hypothalamic pituitary adrenal (HPA) axis in response to stress, of which cortisol is the most prominent in humans.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Results in adults suggest that reduced levels of cortisol, linked to lower fear or a reduced stress response, can be associated with more aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, it may be that proactive aggression is associated with low cortisol levels while reactive aggression may be accompanied by elevated levels.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Differences in assessments of cortisol may also explain a diversity of results, particularly in children.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The HPA axis is related to the general fight-or-flight response or acute stress reaction, and the role of catecholamines such as epinephrine, popularly known as adrenaline.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In many animals, aggression can be linked to pheromones released between conspecifics.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In mice, major urinary proteins (Mups) have been demonstrated to promote innate aggressive behavior in males, and can be mediated by neuromodulatory systems.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Mups activate olfactory sensory neurons in the vomeronasal organ (VNO), a subsystem of the nose known to detect pheromones via specific sensory receptors, of mice and rats.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Pheremones have also been identified in fruit flies, detected by neurons in the antenna, that send a message to the brain eliciting aggression; it has been noted that aggression pheremones have not been identified in humans.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In general, differences in a continuous phenotype such as aggression are likely to result from the action of a large number of genes, each of small effect, which interact with each other and the environment through development and life.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In a non-mammalian example of genes related to aggression, the fruitless gene in fruit flies is a critical determinant of certain sexually dimorphic behaviors, and its artificial alteration can result in a reversal of stereotypically male and female patterns of aggression in fighting.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, in what was thought to be a relatively clear case, inherent complexities have been reported in deciphering the connections between interacting genes in an environmental context and a social phenotype involving multiple behavioral and sensory interactions with another organism.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In mice, candidate genes for differentiating aggression between the sexes are the Sry (sex determining region Y) gene, located on the Y chromosome and the Sts (steroid sulfatase) gene.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The Sts gene encodes the steroid sulfatase enzyme, which is pivotal in the regulation of neurosteroid biosynthesis.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] It is expressed in both sexes, is correlated with levels of aggression among male mice, and increases dramatically in females after parturition and during lactation, corresponding to the onset of maternal aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] At least one study has found a possible epigenetic signature (i.e., decreased methylation at a specific CpG site on the promoter region) of the serotonin receptor 5-HT3a that is associated with maternal aggression among human subjects.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Mice with experimentally elevated sensitivity to oxidative stress (through inhibition of copper-zinc superoxide dismutase, SOD1 activity) were tested for aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Males completely deficient in SOD1 were found to be more aggressive than both wild-type males and males that express 50% of this antioxidant enzyme.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] They were also faster to attack another male.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The causal connection between SOD1 deficiency and increased aggression is not yet understood.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In humans, there is good evidence that the basic human neural architecture underpinning the potential for flexible aggressive responses is influenced by genes as well as environment.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] In terms of variation between individual people, more than 100 twin and adoption studies have been conducted in recent decades examining the genetic basis of aggressive behavior and related constructs such as conduct disorders.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] According to a meta-analysis published in 2002, approximately 40% of variation between individuals is explained by differences in genes, and 60% by differences in environment (mainly non-shared environmental influences rather than those that would be shared by being raised together).
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] However, such studies have depended on self-report or observation by others including parents, which complicates interpretation of the results.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The few laboratory-based analyses have not found significant amounts of individual variation in aggression explicable by genetic variation in the human population.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] Furthermore, linkage and association studies that seek to identify specific genes, for example that influence neurotransmitter or hormone levels, have generally resulted in contradictory findings characterized by failed attempts at replication.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] The generally unclear picture has been compared to equally difficult findings obtained in regard to other complex behavioral phenotypes.
[src:gesture/aggression-p01] For example, both 7R and 5R, ADHD-linked VNTR alleles of dopamine receptor D4 gene are directly associated with the incidence of proactive aggression in the men with no history of ADHD.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Humans share aspects of aggression with non-human animals, and have specific aspects and complexity related to factors such as genetics, early development, social learning and flexibility, culture and morals.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Konrad Lorenz stated in his 1963 classic, *On Aggression,* that human behavior is shaped by four main, survival-seeking animal drives.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Taken together, these drives—hunger, fear, reproduction, and aggression—achieve natural selection.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Wilson elaborated in *On Human Nature* that aggression is, typically, a means of gaining control over resources.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Aggression is, thus, aggravated during times when high population densities generate resource shortages.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] According to Richard Leakey and his colleagues, aggression in humans has also increased by becoming more interested in ownership and by defending his or her property.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, UNESCO adopted the Seville Statement of Violence in 1989 that refuted claims, by evolutionary scientists, that genetics by itself was the sole cause of aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Social and cultural aspects may significantly interfere with the distinct expression of aggressiveness.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] For example, a high population density, when associated with a decrease of available resources, might be a significant intervening variable for the occurrence of violent acts.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Culture is one of the factors that influence aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Tribal or band societies existing before or outside of modern states have sometimes been depicted as peaceful "noble savages".
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The ǃKung people, for instance, were described as "The Harmless People" in a popular work by Elizabeth Marshall Thomas in 1958.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, Lawrence Keeley's 1996 War Before Civilization suggested that regular warfare without modern technology was conducted by most groups throughout human history, including most Native American tribes.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Research on hunter-gatherers has revealed a range of behavioral patterns.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] While aggression, conflict and violence can occur, direct confrontation is generally avoided, and disputes are often managed through various verbal and non-verbal social mechanisms.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Different rates of aggression or violence—whether contemporary or historical—have been associated with social structures and environmental factors such as resource distribution or property acquisition, land use, subsistence strategies, and population dynamics.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Gray likens hunter-gatherer bands to social play groups, while stressing that such play is not frivolous or even easy at all times.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] According to Gray, "Social play—that is, play involving more than one player—is necessarily egalitarian.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] It always requires a suspension of aggression and dominance along with a heightened sensitivity to the needs and desires of the other players".
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Joan Durrant of the University of Manitoba reports that multiple studies have found an association between physical punishment and higher levels of aggression directed toward parents, siblings, peers, and spouses, even when controlling for other influencing factors.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Similarly, Elizabeth Gershoff of the University of Texas at Austin has found that the more frequently children experience physical punishment, the more likely they are, as adults, to engage in violent behavior toward family members, including intimate partners.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In countries where the physical punishment of children is more culturally accepted, its association with increased aggression tends to be weaker.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, research indicates that physical punishment predicts some increase in child aggression regardless of cultural context.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Although these associations do not establish causality, a number of longitudinal studies suggest that experiencing physical punishment can have a direct causal impact on later aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Similar findings were reported in a 2010 study led by Catherine Taylor at Tulane University, which identified a link between maternal spanking of three-year-old children and an increased risk of later aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Straus contends that such evidence has often been overlooked, largely due to a prevailing belief that spanking is more effective than nonviolent forms of discipline.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] He warns, however, that this belief persists despite evidence of harmful side effects.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Cultural and political interpretations of aggression are further complicated by the subjective use of the term "aggressive", which may reflect value judgments depending on the observer's cultural or ideological standpoint.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Whether a coercive or violent act is viewed as aggression—or as legitimate or illegitimate aggression—often depends on the social positions of those involved relative to their culture's structure.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Cross-cultural research has found differences in attitudes towards aggression in different cultures.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Within American culture, men from the southern United States were found in a study of university students to react more strongly and respond more aggressively than their northern counterparts when randomly insulted after being bumped into.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Other cultural frameworks frequently considered in aggression research include contrasts between individualistic and collectivist orientations.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] These may influence how individuals respond to disputes—for example, through open competition or by accommodating others and avoiding conflict.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In a study including 62 countries, school principals reported higher levels of aggressive student behavior in cultures characterized as more individualistic and, correspondingly, less collectivist.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Other cross-cultural comparisons related to aggression and conflict have examined differences between democratic and authoritarian political systems, as well as between egalitarian and stratified societies.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The economic system known as capitalism has been interpreted by some scholars as relying on human competitiveness and aggression to drive the pursuit of resources and trade.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] This perspective has been viewed both positively, as a motivator for innovation and efficiency, and negatively, as a source of inequality and conflict.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Finally, the perceived legitimacy of aggressive acts are influenced by cultural and political attitudes regarding the social acceptability of certain actions or targets.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] These perceptions are often contested, particularly in cases involving religion or international disputes.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] One prominent example is the Arab–Israeli conflict, where acts labeled as aggression by one group may be framed as defense or resistance by another.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Some researchers argue that behaviors such as aggression may be partially learned through observation and imitation of others, a concept rooted in social learning theory.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] This perspective includes the view that exposure to media violence may exert small effects on aggressive behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, this remains a subject of ongoing debate, and other scholars have challenged the strength or consistency of such effects.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] For example, a prospective study of adolescents found no long-term relationship between violent video game use and subsequent youth violence or bullying.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] A meta-analysis concluded that the effect of violent video games on aggression is generally smaller than that found in studies on television violence.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The magnitude of this effect was positively associated with the intensity of violent content and negatively associated with the amount of time spent playing.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The study concluded that the available evidence was insufficient to establish a causal relationship between violent video games and increased aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Conversely, other research has reported associations between violent video game exposure and heightened aggressive thoughts, feelings, and behaviors both in laboratory settings and real-life contexts.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The frequency of physical aggression in humans peaks at around 2–3 years of age.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] These observations suggest that physical aggression is not only a learned behavior but that development provides opportunities for the learning and biological development of self-regulation.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, a small subset of children fail to acquire all the necessary self-regulatory abilities and tend to show atypical levels of physical aggression across development.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] They may be at risk for later violent behavior or, conversely, a lack of aggression that may be considered necessary within society.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, some findings suggest that early aggression does not necessarily lead to aggression later on, although the course through early childhood is an important predictor of outcomes in middle childhood.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In addition, physical aggression that continues is likely occurring in the context of family adversity, including socioeconomic factors.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Moreover, 'opposition' and 'status violations' in childhood appear to be more strongly linked to social problems in adulthood than simply aggressive antisocial behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Social learning through interactions in early childhood has been seen as a building block for levels of aggression which play a crucial role in the development of peer relationships in middle childhood.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Overall, an interplay of biological, social and environmental factors can be considered.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Some research indicates that changes in the weather can increase the likelihood of children exhibiting deviant behavior.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The Bobo doll experiment was conducted by Albert Bandura in 1961.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In this work, Bandura found that children exposed to an aggressive adult model acted more aggressively than those who were exposed to a nonaggressive adult model.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] This experiment suggests that anyone who comes in contact with and interacts with children can affect the way they react and handle situations.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Gender is a factor that plays a role in both human and animal aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Males are historically believed to be generally more physically aggressive than females from an early age, and men commit the vast majority of murders (Buss 2005).
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] This is one of the most robust and reliable behavioral sex differences, and it has been found across many different age groups and cultures.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] However, some empirical studies have found the discrepancy in male and female aggression to be more pronounced in childhood and the gender difference in adults to be modest when studied in an experimental context.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Still, there is evidence that males are quicker to aggression (Frey et al.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] 2003) and more likely than females to express their aggression physically.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] When considering indirect forms of non-violent aggression, such as relational aggression and social rejection, some scientists argue that females can be quite aggressive, although female aggression is rarely expressed physically.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] An exception is intimate partner violence that occurs among couples who are engaged, married, or in some other form of intimate relationship.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Although females are less likely than males to initiate physical violence, they can express aggression by using a variety of non-physical means.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Exactly which method women use to express aggression is something that varies from culture to culture.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] On Bellona Island, a culture based on male dominance and physical violence, women tend to get into conflicts with other women more frequently than with men.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] When in conflict with males, instead of using physical means, they make up songs mocking the man, which spread across the island and humiliate him.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] If a woman wanted to kill a man, she would either convince her male relatives to kill him or hire an assassin.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Although these two methods involve physical violence, both are forms of indirect aggression, since the aggressor herself avoids getting directly involved or putting herself in immediate physical danger.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] See also the sections on testosterone and evolutionary explanations for gender differences above.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] There has been some links between those prone to violence and their alcohol use.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Those who are prone to violence and use alcohol are more likely to carry out violent acts.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Alcohol impairs judgment, making people much less cautious than they usually are (MacDonald et al.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] It also disrupts the way information is processed (Bushman 1993, 1997; Bushman & Cooper 1990).
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Recent research further demonstrates that in everyday situations, violations of social norms can be perceived as provocations that trigger aggression, which can have negative consequences for individuals and social coexistence.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Based on the General Aggression Model (GAM), experimental evidence shows that physical provocation affects the internal state (cognition, arousal, and affect) of the provoked person and shapes their responses.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The social status of the provocateur can play a moderating role in this process: a higher-status provocateur induces a more aggression-prone internal state, but the likelihood of verbal retaliation is less affected by internal state when provocation comes from high status.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] These dynamics, illustrate how intentional provocation reduces the probability of ignoring the incident and increases the likelihood of verbal or physical aggression, mediated by changes in the internal state.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Overall, this mechanism highlights the importance of situational and social factors—such as status—in everyday aggression and its regulation.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] This also adds to the currently inconclusive evidence about the role of the social status on aggression and highlights to importance of further inquiry.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Pain and discomfort also increase aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Even the simple act of placing one's hands in hot water can cause an aggressive response.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Hot temperatures have been implicated as a factor in a number of studies.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] One study completed in the midst of the civil rights movement found that riots were more likely on hotter days than cooler ones (Carlsmith & Anderson 1979).
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Students were found to be more aggressive and irritable after taking a test in a hot classroom (Anderson et al.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Drivers in cars without air conditioning were also found to be more likely to honk their horns (Kenrick & MacFarlane 1986), which is used as a measure of aggression and has shown links to other factors such as generic symbols of aggression or the visibility of other drivers.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Frustration is another major cause of aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The Frustration aggression theory states that aggression increases if a person feels that he or she is being blocked from achieving a goal (Aronson et al.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] One study found that the closeness to the goal makes a difference.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The study examined people waiting in line and concluded that the 2nd person was more aggressive than the 12th one when someone cut in line (Harris 1974).
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Unexpected frustration may be another factor.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In a separate study to demonstrate how unexpected frustration leads to increased aggression, Kulik & Brown (1979) selected a group of students as volunteers to make calls for charity donations.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] One group was told that the people they would call would be generous and the collection would be very successful.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The other group was given no expectations.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] The group that expected success was more upset when no one was pledging than the group who did not expect success (everyone actually had horrible success).
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] This research suggests that when an expectation does not materialize (successful collections), unexpected frustration arises which increases aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] There is some evidence to suggest that the presence of violent objects such as a gun can trigger aggression.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In a study done by Leonard Berkowitz and Anthony Le Page (1967), college students were made angry and then left in the presence of a gun or badminton racket.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] They were then led to believe they were delivering electric shocks to another student, as in the Milgram experiment.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Those who had been in the presence of the gun administered more shocks.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] It is possible that a violence-related stimulus increases the likelihood of aggressive cognitions by activating the semantic network.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] A new proposal links military experience to anger and aggression, developing aggressive reactions and investigating these effects on those possessing the traits of a serial killer.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] They come back to the civilian world and may still be haunted by flashbacks and nightmares, causing severe stress.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] In addition, it has been claimed that in the rare minority who are claimed to be inclined toward serial killing, violent impulses may be reinforced and refined in war, possibly creating more effective murderers.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Some recent scholarship has questioned traditional psychological conceptualizations of aggression as universally negative.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Most traditional psychological definitions of aggression focus on the harm to the recipient of the aggression, implying this is the intent of the aggressor; however this may not always be the case.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] From this alternate view, although the recipient may or may not be harmed, the perceived intent is to increase the status of the aggressor, not necessarily to harm the recipient.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Such scholars contend that traditional definitions of aggression have no validity because of how challenging it is to study directly.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] From this view, rather than concepts such as assertiveness, aggression, violence and criminal violence existing as distinct constructs, they exist instead along a continuum with moderate levels of aggression being most adaptive.
[src:gesture/aggression-p02] Such scholars do not consider this a trivial difference, noting that many traditional researchers' aggression measurements may measure outcomes lower down in the continuum, at levels which are adaptive, yet they generalize their findings to non-adaptive levels of aggression, thus losing precision.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] An **air kiss**, **blown kiss**, or **thrown kiss** is a ritual or social gesture whose meaning is basically the same as that of many forms of kissing.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] The air kiss is a pretence of kissing: the lips are pursed as if kissing, but without actually touching the other person's body.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] Sometimes, the air kiss includes touching cheek-to-cheek.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] Also, the gesture may be accompanied by the *mwah* sound.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] The onomatopoeic word **mwah** (a representation of the sound of a kiss) has entered Webster's dictionary.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] The character block Unicode 1F618 provides the "emoji face throwing a kiss 😘" to computer screens.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] A symbolic kiss is frequent in Western cultures.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] A kiss can be "blown" to another by kissing the fingertips and then blowing the fingertips, pointing them in the direction of the recipient.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] This is used to convey affection, usually when parting or when the partners are physically distant but can view each other.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] Blown kisses are also used when a person wishes to convey affection to a large crowd or audience.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] The term *flying kiss* is used in India to describe a blown kiss.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] In North America and most western countries influenced by North America, air kisses are sometimes associated with glamour models and other celebrities.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] It is a modified cheek kiss, involving kissing in the air near the cheek, with the cheeks touching the lips or not.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] In Indonesia, and Malaysia, it is common to air-kiss an elder's hand as a traditional form of respectful greeting.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] Instead of pursing one's lips, the younger person exhaling through his nose softly on the hand before drawing the hand to the younger person's forehead.
[src:gesture/air-kiss] In the Philippines, elder relatives traditionally kiss a younger relative's cheek in this same way, by exhaling gently through the nose when the younger relative's cheek is brought close.
[src:gesture/gesture] A **gesture** is a form of nonverbal communication or non-vocal communication in which visible bodily actions communicate particular messages, either in place of, or in conjunction with, speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures include movement of the hands, face, or other parts of the body.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures differ from physical non-verbal communication that does not communicate specific messages, such as purely expressive displays, proxemics, or displays of joint attention.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures allow individuals to communicate a variety of feelings and thoughts, from contempt and hostility to approval and affection, often together with body language in addition to words when they speak.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gesticulation and speech work independently of each other, but join to provide emphasis and meaning.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gesture processing takes place in areas of the brain such as Broca's and Wernicke's areas, which are used by speech and sign language.
[src:gesture/gesture] In fact, language is thought by some scholars to have evolved in *Homo sapiens* from an earlier system consisting of manual gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] The theory that language evolved from manual gestures, termed Gestural Theory, dates back to the work of 18th-century philosopher and priest Abbé de Condillac, and has been revived by contemporary anthropologist Gordon W.
[src:gesture/gesture] Hewes, in 1973, as part of a discussion on the origin of language.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures have been studied throughout time from different philosophers.
[src:gesture/gesture] Marcus Fabius Quintilianus was a Roman Rhetorician who studied in his Institutio Oratoria on how gesture can be used on rhetorical discourses.
[src:gesture/gesture] One of his greatest works and foundation for communication was the "Institutio Oratoria" where he explains his observations and nature of different oratories.
[src:gesture/gesture] A study done in 1644, by John Bulwer an English physician and early Baconian natural philosopher wrote five works exploring human communications pertaining to gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] Bulwer analyzed dozens of gestures and provided a guide under his book named Chirologia which focused on hand gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] In the 19th century, Andrea De Jorio an Italian antiquarian who considered a lot of research about body language published an extensive account of gesture expressions.
[src:gesture/gesture] Meltzoff an American psychologist internationally renown for infant and child development conducted a study in 1977 on the imitation of facial and manual gestures by newborns.
[src:gesture/gesture] The study concluded that "infants between 12 and 21 days of age can imitate the facial and manual gestures of parents".
[src:gesture/gesture] A peer-reviewed journal Gesture has been published since 2001, and was founded by Adam Kendon and Cornelia Müller.
[src:gesture/gesture] The International Society for Gesture Studies (ISGS) was founded in 2002.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gesture has frequently been taken up by researchers in the field of dance studies and performance studies in ways that emphasize the ways they are culturally and contextually inflected.
[src:gesture/gesture] Performance scholar Carrie Noland describes gestures as "learned techniques of the body" and stresses the way gestures are embodied corporeal forms of cultural communication.
[src:gesture/gesture] But rather than just residing within one cultural context, she describes how gestures migrate across bodies and locations to create new cultural meanings and associations.
[src:gesture/gesture] She also posits how they might function as a form of "resistance to homogenization" because they are so dependent on the specification of the bodies that perform them.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gesture has also been taken up within queer theory, ethnic studies and their intersections in performance studies, as a way to think about how the moving body gains social meaning.
[src:gesture/gesture] José Esteban Muñoz uses the idea of gesture to mark a kind of refusal of finitude and certainty and links gesture to his ideas of ephemera.
[src:gesture/gesture] Muñoz specifically draws on the African-American dancer and drag queen performer Kevin Aviance to articulate his interest not in what queer gestures might mean, but what they might perform.
[src:gesture/gesture] Juana María Rodríguez borrows ideas of phenomenology and draws on Noland and Muñoz to investigate how gesture functions in queer sexual practices as a way to rewrite gender and negotiate power relations.
[src:gesture/gesture] She also connects gesture to Giorgio Agamben's idea of "means without ends" to think about political projects of social justice that are incomplete, partial, and legibile within culturally and socially defined spheres of meaning.
[src:gesture/gesture] Since the late 1990s, most research has revolved around the contrasting hypothesis that Lexical gestures serve a primarily cognitive purpose in aiding the process of speech production.
[src:gesture/gesture] As of 2012, there is research to suggest that Lexical Gesture does indeed serve a primarily communicative purpose and cognitive only secondary, but in the realm of socio-pragmatic communication, rather than lexico-semantic modification.
[src:gesture/gesture] Humans have the ability to communicate through language, but they can also express through gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] In particular, gestures can be transmitted through movements of body parts, face, and body expressions.
[src:gesture/gesture] Researchers Goldin Meadow and Brentari D. conducted research in 2015 and concluded that communicating through sign language is no different from spoken language.
[src:gesture/gesture] The first way to distinguish between categories of gesture is to differentiate between communicative gesture and informative gesture.
[src:gesture/gesture] While most gestures can be defined as possibly happening during the course of spoken utterances, the informative-communicative dichotomy focuses on intentionality of meaning and communication in co-speech gesture.
[src:gesture/gesture] Informative gestures are passive gestures that provide information about the speaker as a person and not about what the speaker is trying to communicate.
[src:gesture/gesture] Some movements are not purely considered gestures, however a person could perform these adapters in such way like scratching, adjusting clothing, and tapping.
[src:gesture/gesture] These gestures can occur during speech, but they may also occur independently of communication, as they are not a part of active communication.
[src:gesture/gesture] While informative gestures may communicate information about the person speaking (e.g. itchy, uncomfortable, etc.), this communication is not engaged with any language being produced by the person gesturing.
[src:gesture/gesture] Army recruitment poster of Uncle Sam, he is pointing and sending a non-verbal form of gesture by implying he wants the viewer to join the U.S.
[src:gesture/gesture] This is a form of symbolic gesture, usually used in the absence of speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] Body language is a form of nonverbal communication that allows visual cues that transmit messages without speaking.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are movement that are made with the body: arms, hands, facial, etc.
[src:gesture/gesture] Barbara and Allan Pease, authors of *The Definitive Book of Body Language*, concluded that everyone does a shoulder shrug, a gesture signifying that the person is not comprehending what they are supposed to be understanding.
[src:gesture/gesture] Also, that showing the palms of both hands to show a person is not hiding anything, and raising the eyebrows to indicate a greeting.
[src:gesture/gesture] Finger gestures are commonly used in a variety of ways, from point at something to indicate that you want to show a person something to indicating a thumbs up to show everything is good.
[src:gesture/gesture] Some gestures are near universals, i.e., found all over the world with only some exceptions.
[src:gesture/gesture] An example is the head shake to signify "no".
[src:gesture/gesture] Also, in most cultures nodding your head signifies "Yes", which the book "The Definitive Book of Body Language" describes as submissive gesture to representing the conversation is going the direction of the person speaking.
[src:gesture/gesture] The book explains that people who are born deaf can show a form of submissive gesture to signify "Yes".
[src:gesture/gesture] Within the realm of communicative gestures, the first distinction to be made is between gestures made with the hands and arms, and gestures made with other parts of the body.
[src:gesture/gesture] Examples of Non-manual gestures may include head nodding and shaking, shoulder shrugging, and facial expression, among others.
[src:gesture/gesture] Non-manual gestures are attested in languages all around the world, but have not been the primary focus of most research regarding co-speech gesture.
[src:gesture/gesture] A gesture that is a form of communication in which bodily actions communicate particular messages.
[src:gesture/gesture] The most familiar are the so-called emblems or quotable gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] These are conventional, culture-specific gestures that can be used as replacement for words, such as the handwave used in the US for "hello" and "goodbye".
[src:gesture/gesture] A single emblematic gesture can have a very different significance in different cultural contexts, ranging from complimentary to highly offensive.
[src:gesture/gesture] The page List of gestures discusses emblematic gestures made with one hand, two hands, hand and other body parts, and body and facial gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] Symbolic gestures can occur either concurrently or independently of vocal speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] Symbolic gestures are iconic gestures that are widely recognized, fixed, and have conventionalized meanings.
[src:gesture/gesture] Deictic gestures can occur simultaneously with vocal speech or in place of it.
[src:gesture/gesture] Deictic gestures are gestures that consist of indicative or pointing motions.
[src:gesture/gesture] These gestures often work in the same way as demonstrative words and pronouns like "this" or "that".
[src:gesture/gesture] Deictic gestures can refer to concrete or intangible objects or people.
[src:gesture/gesture] Motor or beat gestures usually consist of short, repetitive, rhythmic movements that are closely tied with prosody in verbal speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] Unlike symbolic and deictic gestures, beat gestures cannot occur independently of verbal speech and convey no semantic information.
[src:gesture/gesture] For example, some people wave their hands as they speak to emphasize a certain word or phrase.
[src:gesture/gesture] These gestures are closely coordinated with speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] The so-called beat gestures are used in conjunction with speech and keep time with the rhythm of speech to emphasize certain words or phrases.
[src:gesture/gesture] These types of gestures are integrally connected to speech and thought processes.
[src:gesture/gesture] Other spontaneous gestures used during speech production known as iconic gestures are more full of content, and may echo, or elaborate, the meaning of the co-occurring speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] They depict aspects of spatial images, actions, people, or objects.
[src:gesture/gesture] For example, a gesture that depicts the act of throwing may be synchronous with the utterance, "He threw the ball right into the window." Such gestures that are used along with speech tend to be universal.
[src:gesture/gesture] For example, one describing that they are feeling cold due to a lack of proper clothing and/or a cold weather can accompany their verbal description with a visual one.
[src:gesture/gesture] This can be achieved through various gestures such as by demonstrating a shiver and/or by rubbing the hands together.
[src:gesture/gesture] The elaboration of lexical gestures falls on a spectrum of iconic-metaphorical in how closely tied they are to the lexico-semantic content of the verbal speech they coordinate with.
[src:gesture/gesture] Lexical gestures, like motor gestures, cannot occur independently of verbal speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] The purpose of lexical gestures is still widely contested in the literature with some linguists arguing that lexical gestures serve to amplify or modulate the semantic content of lexical speech, or that it serves a cognitive purpose in aiding in lexical access and retrieval or verbal working memory.
[src:gesture/gesture] Most recent research suggests that lexical gestures serve a primarily socio-pragmatic role.
[src:gesture/gesture] Studies affirm a strong link between gesture typology and language development.
[src:gesture/gesture] Young children under the age of two seem to rely on pointing gestures to refer to objects that they do not know the names of.
[src:gesture/gesture] Once the words are learned, they eschewed those referential (pointing) gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] One would think that the use of gesture would decrease as the child develops spoken language, but results reveal that gesture frequency increased as speaking frequency increased with age.
[src:gesture/gesture] There is, however, a change in gesture typology at different ages, suggesting a connection between gestures and language development.
[src:gesture/gesture] Children most often use pointing and adults rely more on iconic and beat gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] As children begin producing sentence-like utterances, they also begin producing new kinds of gestures that adults use when speaking (iconics and beats).
[src:gesture/gesture] Evidence of this systematic organization of gesture is indicative of its association to language development.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestural languages such as American Sign Language operate as complete natural languages that are gestural in modality.
[src:gesture/gesture] They should not be confused with finger spelling, in which a set of emblematic gestures are used to represent a written alphabet.
[src:gesture/gesture] Sign languages are different from gesturing in that concepts are modeled by certain hand motions or expressions and has a specific established structure while gesturing is more malleable and has no specific structure rather it supplements speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] Before an established sign language was created in Nicaragua after the 1970s, deaf Nicaraguans would use "home signs" in order to communicate with others.
[src:gesture/gesture] These home signs were not part of a unified language but were still used as familiar motions and expressions used within their family—still closely related to language rather than gestures with no specific structure.
[src:gesture/gesture] Home signs are similar to the gestural actions of chimpanzees.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are used by these animals in place of verbal language, which is restricted in animals due to their lacking certain physiological and articulation abilities that humans have for speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] The function of gestures may have been a significant player in the evolution of language.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gesturing is probably universal; there has been no report of a community that does not gesture.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are a crucial part of everyday conversation such as chatting, describing a route, negotiating prices on a market; they are ubiquitous.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are learned embodied cultural practices that can function as a way to interpret ethnic, gender, and sexual identity.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures, commonly referred to as "body language", play an important role in industry.
[src:gesture/gesture] Proper body language etiquette in business dealings can be crucial for success.
[src:gesture/gesture] However, gestures can have different meanings according to the country in which they are expressed.
[src:gesture/gesture] In an age of global business, diplomatic cultural sensitivity has become a necessity.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures that we take as innocent may be seen by someone else as deeply insulting.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are also a means to initiate a mating ritual.
[src:gesture/gesture] This may include elaborate dances and other movements.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures play a major role in many aspects of human life.
[src:gesture/gesture] Additionally, when people use gestures, there is a certain shared background knowledge.
[src:gesture/gesture] Different cultures use similar gestures when talking about a specific action such as how we gesture the idea of drinking out of a cup.
[src:gesture/gesture] When an individual makes a gesture, another person can understand because of recognition of the actions/shapes.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures have been documented in the arts such as in Greek vase paintings, Indian Miniatures or European paintings.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures play a central role in religious or spiritual rituals.
[src:gesture/gesture] In Hinduism and Buddhism, a *mudra* (Sanskrit, literally "seal", "gesture" or "attitude") is a symbolic gesture made with the hand, body or mind.
[src:gesture/gesture] Each mudra has a specific meaning, and is associated with a specific spiritual quality or state.
[src:gesture/gesture] In yoga, mudras are considered to be higher practices which lead to awakening of the pranas, chakras and kundalini, and which can bestow major siddhis, psychic powers, on the advanced practitioner.
[src:gesture/gesture] In Hindu and Buddhist iconography mudras play a central role.
[src:gesture/gesture] For example, Vitarka Vicara, the gesture of discussion and transmission of Buddhist teaching, is done by joining the tips of the thumb and the index together, while keeping the other fingers straight.
[src:gesture/gesture] A common Christian religious gesture is crossing oneself as a sign of respect, also known as making the sign of the cross; often this is accompanied by kneeling before a sacred object.
[src:gesture/gesture] In the renewal of the Catholic liturgy promoted by the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s, "actions, gestures, and bodily attitudes" were noted as means by which a whole worshipping community could participate in the liturgical action.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are processed in the same areas of the brain as speech and sign language such as the left inferior frontal gyrus (Broca's area) and the posterior middle temporal gyrus, posterior superior temporal sulcus and superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke's area).
[src:gesture/gesture] It has been suggested that these parts of the brain originally supported the pairing of gesture and meaning and then were adapted in human evolution "for the comparable pairing of sound and meaning as voluntary control over the vocal apparatus was established and spoken language evolved".
[src:gesture/gesture] As a result, it underlies both symbolic gesture and spoken language in the present human brain.
[src:gesture/gesture] Their common neurological basis also supports the idea that symbolic gesture and spoken language are two parts of a single fundamental semiotic system that underlies human discourse.
[src:gesture/gesture] The linkage of hand and body gestures in conjunction with speech is further revealed by the nature of gesture use in blind individuals during conversation.
[src:gesture/gesture] This phenomenon uncovers a function of gesture that goes beyond portraying communicative content of language and extends David McNeill's view of the gesture-speech system.
[src:gesture/gesture] This suggests that gesture and speech work tightly together, and a disruption of one (speech or gesture) will cause a problem in the other.
[src:gesture/gesture] Studies have found strong evidence that speech and gesture are innately linked in the brain and work in an efficiently wired and choreographed system.
[src:gesture/gesture] McNeill's view of this linkage in the brain is just one of three currently up for debate; the others declaring gesture to be a "support system" of spoken language or a physical mechanism for lexical retrieval.
[src:gesture/gesture] Because of this connection of co-speech gestures—a form of manual action—in language in the brain, Roel Willems and Peter Hagoort conclude that both gestures and language contribute to the understanding and decoding of a speaker's encoded message.
[src:gesture/gesture] Because gestures aided in understanding the relayed message, there was not as great a need for semantic selection or control that would otherwise be required of the listener through Broca's area.
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures are a way to represent the thoughts of an individual, which are prompted in working memory.
[src:gesture/gesture] The researchers found that those with low capacity of working memory who were able to use gestures actually recalled more terms than those with low capacity who were not able to use gestures.
[src:gesture/gesture] The movement of gestures can be used to interact with technology like computers, using touch or multi-touch popularised by the iPhone, physical movement detection and visual motion capture, used in video game consoles.
[src:gesture/gesture] It can be recorded using kinematic methodology.
[src:gesture/gesture] In order to better understand the linguistic values that gestures hold, Adam Kendon, a pioneer in gesture research has proposed to look at it as a continuum from less linguistic to fully linguistic.
[src:gesture/gesture] Using the continuum, speech declines as "the language-like properties of gestural behaviors increase and idiosyncratic gestures are replaced by socially regulated signs".
[src:gesture/gesture] Gestures of different kinds fall within this continuum and include spontaneous gesticulations, language-like gestures, pantomime, emblems, and sign language.
[src:gesture/gesture] Spontaneous gesticulations are not evident without the presence of speech, assisting in the process of vocalization, whereas language-like gestures are "iconic and metaphoric, but lack consistency and are context-dependent".
[src:gesture/gesture] "Language-like gesture" implies that the gesture is assuming something linguistic (Loncke, 2013).
[src:gesture/gesture] Pantomime falls in the middle of the continuum and requires shared conventions.
[src:gesture/gesture] This kind of gesture helps convey information or describe an event.
[src:gesture/gesture] Following pantomime are emblems, which have specific meanings to denote "feelings, obscenities, and insults" and are not required to be used in conjunction with speech.
[src:gesture/gesture] The most linguistic gesture on Kendon's continuum is sign language, where "single manual signs have specific meanings and are combined with other manual signs according to specific rules".
